CHAP. V.
I Shall not
stop
to record the minute
incidents
that took place in the
course
of
this day's travel; or that of the two
following
days; or relate the particulars of the
conversation
of the Captain with Duncan,
or of Duncan with any other
person
. What
I have related, was chiefly with a view to
give
some
idea of the new valet's character
and manners.
I think it was the fourth day after
leaving
the city, that the Captain
casting
up
his eyes at a place where there was a
considerable
length of
straightroad
before him,
saw
a
person
trudging on foot, who by his
make and gait, appeared to him to
resemthe
new revenue officer, the quondam
bog-trotter
.
Duncan,
said
the Captain, if that
man was not on foot, that is before us, I
should
take him for Teague O'Regan, the
waiting man that was in my
service
, and
who gave place to you; having obtained
a
a
commission
in the revenue, and become
an
