CHAP. VIII.
ON the third day renewing their
journey
,
the
conversation
between the
Captain and his
servant
turned on the
character, and
history
of the
present
revenue
officer, the late Teague O'Regan.
The Captain gave Duncan a relation of
what had happened; in the
case
of the
attempt
to draw him off to the
Philosophical
Society, to induce him to preach, and even
to take a
seat
in the
legislature
of the
United
States; that had it not been for a
certain
Traddle, a weaver, whom they had been
fortunate enough to
substitute
for him,
the people would
most
undoubtedly have
elected Teague, and
sent
him to
Congress
.
Guid deliver us!
said
Duncan; do they
make Parliament men o' weavers i' this
kintra? In Scotland, it maun be a duke,
or a laird, that can hae a
seat
there.
This is a republic, Duncan,
said
the
cap
F 2
Captain; and the rights of man are
understood
,
and
exercised
by the people.
And if he could be i' the
Congress
, why
did ye let him be a gauger?
said
Duncan.
This is all the prejudice of education,
Duncan,
said
the Captain. An
appointment
in the revenue, under the executive
of the United States, ought not to have
disgrace
